Chapter 7: Self‑Diagnostics and Meta‑Recursion

7.1 Recursive Self‑Modeling with Martingale Monitors

The self‑model \mathcal{M}_{\text{self}} is itself a contracting system with a known ISS gain. The divergence \delta_k = \|s_k - \hat{s}_k\| forms a supermartingale under normal operation. The system can detect anomalies by checking whether \delta_k violates the Azuma–Hoeffding bounds.

Theorem 7.1 (Self‑Model Anomaly Detection)
If both the main system and the self‑model are ISS and the coupling between them is sufficiently weak, then the divergence process satisfies the martingale property, and the probability of false anomaly detection can be made arbitrarily small by choosing appropriate thresholds.

Proof. Similar to Theorem 4.2, the divergence can be expressed as a supermartingale difference sequence. The Azuma–Hoeffding inequality provides exponential bounds. □

7.2 Structural Plasticity

When a cognitive agent learns a new fault pattern, it modifies its internal representation. Any such modification must be validated against the SOS‑computed contraction metric. The software enforces that learning updates are performed only after a sufficient number of samples are collected, and the updated parameters are checked to ensure the Lipschitz constant remains below 1 and that the new metric is still positive definite over the region.

